TY  - JOUR
TI  - Sustainable land management and climate adaptation: Current practices and future needs in Namibia
AU  - Aryee, J. N. A.
AU  - Chigbu, U. E.
AU  - Mwando, S. M.
AU  - Gilbert, J.
T2  - Local Development & Society
AB  - Land degradation neutrality frames global restoration commitments, yet degradation threatens climate-vulnerable communities’ livelihoods, health, and security. Sustainable land management (SLM) offers a key pathway to climate resilience and reversing degradation. Namibia, facing severe climate impacts, requires strategies that integrate land restoration with adaptation. This review examines synergies between SLM and climate adaptation, identifying practices that boost productivity, biodiversity, ecosystem restoration, and enhances resilience. A search of 3 databases yielded 347 papers, with 111 screened for analysis. Findings highlight conservation agriculture, agroforestry, rotational grazing, and community-based natural resource management as vital for sustainable resource use and local empowerment. SLM-aligned policy frameworks are essential to improve monitoring, private sector engagement, and renewable energy integration. The review calls for policy integration, active community engagement, and increased financial support for SLM. We recommend formal integration of SLM into national adaptation policies, backed by community governance, targeted climate finance, robust monitoring, and private sector engagement. Sustainable land management must serve as the backbone of climate adaptation strategies at both national and local levels in Namibia.Community-based adaptation models, including conservancies and rotational grazing systems, provide proven and scalable pathways for climate resilience.Secure land tenure and strong community participation are essential for effective and sustained climate adaptation outcomes.Climate-smart and technologically enabled agriculture enhances productivity, ecosystem resilience, and efficient resource management.Effective climate adaptation requires strengthened institutional coordination and a multi-stakeholder approach across land, water, and disaster risk sectors. Sustainable land management must serve as the backbone of climate adaptation strategies at both national and local levels in Namibia. Community-based adaptation models, including conservancies and rotational grazing systems, provide proven and scalable pathways for climate resilience. Secure land tenure and strong community participation are essential for effective and sustained climate adaptation outcomes. Climate-smart and technologically enabled agriculture enhances productivity, ecosystem resilience, and efficient resource management. Effective climate adaptation requires strengthened institutional coordination and a multi-stakeholder approach across land, water, and disaster risk sectors.
